## v1.2.0 (2026-06-08)

Amend (verified-ci): existing-PR review handler must RE-ENTER the loop on NO-GO
(short-circuit on GO ONLY), and the existing-PR worktree must use the PR's REAL
`headRefName` instead of an assumed `{issue}-auto-impl` branch.

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PRs #1104 (NO-GO re-review) + #1106 (real PR head branch).
**Verification:** verified-ci (both shipped to ProjectHephaestus main; all CI green).

What changed in the canonical `.md`:

- **Description / When-to-Use / tags:** added triggers (10) an existing-PR review
  handler short-circuits NO-GO PRs as if settled (`if has_go or has_no_go: skip`) so a
  failed-review PR never re-enters the loop, and (11) an existing-PR worktree sync fails
  `git fetch origin {issue}-auto-impl` (exit 128) because the head branch was ASSUMED from
  the issue number instead of read from the PR's real `headRefName`. New tags:
  `existing-pr-short-circuit`, `no-go-re-review`, `go-only-short-circuit`,
  `pr-head-branch-resolution`, `headrefname`, `assumed-branch-name-fetch-128`.
- **New Verified-Workflow subsection** "Existing-PR handler: short-circuit on GO ONLY, and
  use the PR's real head branch" documenting both invariants.
- **Two new Failed-Attempts rows** (GO-or-NO-GO short-circuit; assumed `{issue}-auto-impl`
  fetch) and **two new convergence-contract rows** (GO-only short-circuit; real head branch).
- **Two new "Verified On" rows** for PR #1104 and PR #1106.
- Version `1.1.0` → `1.2.0`; date `2026-06-07` → `2026-06-08`.

Why:

- **Learning A (PR #1104):** the existing-PR handler `_review_existing_pr`
  (`hephaestus/automation/implementer_phase_runner.py`) had an idempotency short-circuit
  `if has_go or has_no_go: return`, treating a `state:implementation-no-go` PR as
  terminal/settled — identical to a GO PR. In a live 5-loop run all 60 existing PRs carried
  a terminal label (10 GO, 50 NO-GO), so every PR was skipped every loop (`Successful: 0 /
  Skipped: 60`) and the fallback `drive-green` phase was itself skipped — NO-GO PRs were
  NEVER re-implemented or re-reviewed. Fix: short-circuit on `has_go` ONLY; a NO-GO PR falls
  through into `_run_impl_review_loop` (NO-GO → resume implementer session → re-review →
  converge-on-GO), bounded by `MAX_REVIEW_ITERATIONS`, gating a re-run on the PR head SHA
  advancing to avoid burning tokens on a stuck PR. This is the same "a NO-GO is NOT terminal;
  a re-open OVERRIDES a stale GO" principle the skill already states, applied at the
  existing-PR layer.
- **Learning B (PR #1106):** a LATENT bug EXPOSED by Learning A's fix. `_review_existing_pr`
  prepared the worktree with `branch_name = f"{issue_number}-auto-impl"` (an ASSUMPTION) and
  called `sync_worktree_to_remote_branch` → `git fetch origin {issue}-auto-impl`, failing
  `fatal: couldn't find remote ref …; exit 128` whenever the PR's head branch differs from
  the convention. Root cause: `find_pr_for_issue` (`_review_utils.py`) can match a PR via a
  PR-body `Closes #N` search (strategy 2), so the head branch may belong to a DIFFERENT issue
  or bundle (confirmed live: issue #725 → PR #996, real `headRefName` `708-auto-impl`). Before
  #1104, NO-GO PRs short-circuited before reaching the fetch, so it never fired for them. Fix:
  added `get_pr_head_branch(pr_number)` to `_review_utils` (`gh pr view <pr> --json
  headRefName`; returns `None` on failure for a safe fallback); `_review_existing_pr` resolves
  the real head branch and uses it for worktree create + sync + review loop + `WorkerResult`,
  falling back to the assumed name only on `None`. The fresh-implementation path keeps the
  convention because it creates the branch itself. Test note: tests exercising this path MUST
  mock `get_pr_head_branch` or they hit a real `gh` call (a test took 103s before mocking).

